Summing contributions

In a particle‐in‐cell (PIC) simulation the “current” through a surface is nothing other than the net flux of charge that crosses that surface per unit time. In your case you want the current crossing an arbitrary plane at a given z=Zz=Zz=Z. One common strategy is to “deposit” the particle current onto the grid, but if you want to compute the current directly from the particle data then you need to:

  1. Identify which particles are “crossing” the plane during the time step.
    For each particle you have both the old position (at time ttt) and the new position (at time t+Δtt+\Delta tt+Δt). If the particle’s zzz coordinate was on one side of the plane at time ttt (say, zold<Zz_{\text{old}} < Zzold​<Z) and on the other side at time t+Δtt+\Delta tt+Δt (i.e. znew>Zz_{\text{new}} > Zznew​>Z), then the particle has crossed the plane during this time step. (The same applies if the particle goes from above to below.)
    Mathematically, you can test for a crossing with the condition:

    (zold−Z)×(znew−Z)<0.(z_{\text{old}}-Z) \times (z_{\text{new}}-Z) < 0.(zold​−Z)×(znew​−Z)<0.

  2. Estimate the particle’s contribution to the current.
    The basic idea is that the current is the rate at which charge passes through the surface. Suppose a particle of charge qqq crosses the plane; if you assume a linear trajectory during the time step, then the “amount” of charge crossing the plane per unit time is roughly q/Δtq/\Delta tq/Δt. (If you want to be more precise you could compute the exact crossing time via linear interpolation.)

    Alternatively, if you are “depositing” current in a grid‐based manner (using a shape function), then the contribution from a particle might be

    jz=q vz S(x,y)j_z = q\, v_z \, S(x,y)jz​=qvz​S(x,y)

    where S(x,y)S(x,y)S(x,y) is the interpolation (or “shape”) weight that tells you what fraction of the particle’s current goes to a given grid cell along the plane.

    For a simple “particle crossing” count, however, you simply add q/Δtq/\Delta tq/Δt (with the proper sign, since electrons have negative charge) for every crossing particle.

  3. Sum over all particles.
    The net current IzI_zIz​ through the plane (or the current density, if you normalize by the plane’s area) is then given by summing the contributions from all particles that cross. In pseudocode this might look like:

    julia
    I_z = 0.0
for i in 1:N_particles
    z_old = particle.PosArray_old[3, i]
    z_new = particle.PosArray[3, i]
    # Check if the particle crossed the plane at z = Z
    if (z_old - Z) * (z_new - Z) < 0
        # You can also find the exact crossing time:
        t_cross = Δt * abs(Z - z_old) / abs(z_new - z_old)
        # For a first-order estimate, assume the entire charge crosses:
        I_z += particle.qArray[i] / Δt
    end
end

    Here the sign of qqq (positive for ions, negative for electrons) automatically gives you the proper sense of “direction” for the current. If you are interested in the current density jzj_zjz​, then divide the total current by the area of the plane.

  4. (Optionally) Use weighted contributions.
    In many PIC codes each “super-particle” represents many physical particles. Your superParticleSizeArray contains that weight. In that case, you would scale the contribution of each particle by its weight:

    ΔIz=q wΔt,\Delta I_z = \frac{q\, w}{\Delta t},ΔIz​=Δtqw​,

    where www is the super-particle weight (the number of real particles it represents).

    So in code, you might do:

    julia
    I_z = 0.0
for i in 1:N_particles
    z_old = particle.PosArray_old[3, i]
    z_new = particle.PosArray[3, i]
    if (z_old - Z) * (z_new - Z) < 0
        weight = particle.superParticleSizeArray[i]
        I_z += (particle.qArray[i] * weight) / Δt
    end
end

  5. Consider Deposition Schemes.
    In many PIC implementations the “current deposition” step is done continuously by weighting the particle’s contribution to nearby grid nodes (for example using linear or higher‐order weighting methods). In that approach the current at the grid nodes adjacent to the plane is computed by summing q vzq\, v_zqvz​ multiplied by the shape function, and then the current crossing the plane is reconstructed from the grid values. This method is often more accurate and avoids the need to “detect” crossings explicitly. If your code already deposits charge to the grid (as it appears to with fields like ionflux and electronflux in your domain class), you might simply sum the deposited current in the cells adjacent to z=Zz = Zz=Z and then multiply by the cell’s cross-sectional area.

Summary

  • Step 1: Loop over all particles and check if the zzz-coordinate has “crossed” the plane at z=Zz=Zz=Z between ttt and t+Δtt+\Delta tt+Δt.
  • Step 2: For every crossing particle, compute its contribution. For a simple estimate, add q×(superparticle weight)/Δtq \times (\text{superparticle weight})/\Delta tq×(superparticle weight)/Δt.
  • Step 3: Sum all these contributions to obtain the total current across the plane (or the current density if normalized by area).

This method gives you a direct way to compute the current from your particle data. Alternatively, if you are using a deposition scheme for fields, you may already have grid‐based currents (for example, stored in ionflux and electronflux) that can be summed over the cells that intersect your z=Zz=Zz=Z plane.

Yes, that's exactly one interpretation. In point 2, there are two common ways to compute the current:

  1. Global (Net) Current:
    If you're only interested in the overall current crossing the plane, you can simply add up the contributions from each particle that crosses—essentially summing ΔIz=q (or q×weight)/Δt\Delta I_z = q \, (\text{or } q \times \text{weight})/\Delta tΔIz​=q(or q×weight)/Δt for each crossing event. This gives you a single number representing the net current through the plane.

  2. Spatial Distribution of the Current Density jz(x,y)j_z(x,y)jz​(x,y):
    Alternatively, if you want to know how the current is distributed across the plane (i.e., the current density as a function of the xxx and yyy coordinates), you would deposit the contribution from each particle onto a grid along the plane. In this case, you use a shape (or weighting) function S(x,y)S(x,y)S(x,y) that spreads the particle's contribution over the nearby grid nodes. For example, a particle with charge qqq and velocity component vzv_zvz​ might contribute an amount

    jz(x,y)=q vz S(x,y)j_z(x,y) = q\, v_z\, S(x,y)jz​(x,y)=qvz​S(x,y)

    to the grid. Summing these contributions over all particles gives you a spatial map of jz(x,y)j_z(x,y)jz​(x,y) over the plane at z=Zz=Zz=Z.

Which method you choose depends on whether you need a single net current value or a detailed spatial profile of the current density.

Below is one example of how you might “complete” your flux‐analysis function. In this example we assume that you want to record, for a control volume (CV) defined by two zzz boundaries Z0Z_0Z0​ and Z1Z_1Z1​, the following quantities (per time step):

  1. The net charge (current) leaving/entering the CV at the two boundaries. We separate the contributions from ions (with positive charge) and electrons (with negative charge). (In other words, for every particle that “crosses” one of the two boundaries we add its contribution—qqq times the particle’s weight—divided by the time step, with a sign chosen so that particles leaving the CV contribute positively while those entering subtract.)
  2. The net momentum flux in the zzz direction (again using the particle’s zzz‐momentum m vzm\,v_zmvz​ multiplied by its weight).
  3. As an aside, we also “deposit” the energy (kinetic plus potential) and the net charge for particles that remain inside the CV.

In a PIC code you must decide whether you want a “grid‐based deposition” (where each particle’s contribution is spread onto nearby grid nodes by a shape function) or a “crossing‐detection” method (where you check the old and new particle positions to decide if it crossed a boundary). In the code below we follow the latter approach.

Because many threads may be updating the same output variable, we use CUDA’s atomic operations. (Also note that here the kernel is written as an inner function so that many of the needed arrays from your Particle_GPU and RZDomain_GPU objects are “captured” and passed along.) Finally, note that the contributions are computed “per time‐step” so that if you later want to obtain a physical current you must divide by the time step Δt\Delta tΔt.

One possible complete implementation is as follows:

julia
using CUDA

# The complete flux analysis function.
# (We add a dt parameter for the time step.)
function CV_fluxanalysis(myParticle::Particle_GPU, myDomain::RZDomain_GPU, Z0::Float64, Z1::Float64, dt::Float64)
    # Allocate one-element arrays on the GPU to accumulate our results.
    EnergyArray         = CUDA.zeros(Float64, 1)
    ChargeArray         = CUDA.zeros(Float64, 1)
    IonCurrentArray     = CUDA.zeros(Float64, 1)
    ElectronCurrentArray= CUDA.zeros(Float64, 1)
    MomentumFluxArray   = CUDA.zeros(Float64, 1)

    # Define the kernel that will run on the GPU.
    function CV_fluxanalysis_kernel(
            PosArray, PosArray_old,
            VelArray, VelArray_old,
            alive, 
            qArray, 
            mArray,
            superParticleSizeArray,
            rCellNum, zCellNum,
            phi,
            dt,
            EnergyArray, ChargeArray,
            IonCurrentArray, ElectronCurrentArray,
            MomentumFluxArray)
        
        idx = threadIdx().x + (blockIdx().x - 1) * blockDim().x
        if idx <= length(alive)
            if alive[idx] == 1
                # Current particle z-position and previous z-position
                z    = PosArray[3, idx]
                zold = PosArray_old[3, idx]
                q    = qArray[idx]
                weight = superParticleSizeArray[idx]

                # Compute z-momentum (include the weight of the super-particle)
                momentum = mArray[idx] * VelArray[3, idx] * weight

                # Compute total energy (kinetic + potential)
                # (Assuming that 'gather' is a helper function that obtains the value of phi
                #  at the cell given by (rCellNum[idx], zCellNum[idx]).)
                kinetic = weight * mArray[idx] * (VelArray[1,idx]^2 + VelArray[2,idx]^2 + VelArray[3,idx]^2)
                potential = weight * q * gather(phi, rCellNum[idx], zCellNum[idx])
                energy = kinetic + potential

                # --- Right boundary at z = Z1 ---
                if (z > Z1 && zold <= Z1)
                    # Particle leaves the CV on the right.
                    # (Contribution: + (q*weight)/dt and + momentum/dt)
                    contrib = (q * weight) / dt
                    if q > 0
                        @CUDA.atomic IonCurrentArray[1] += contrib
                    else
                        @CUDA.atomic ElectronCurrentArray[1] += contrib
                    end
                    @CUDA.atomic MomentumFluxArray[1] += momentum / dt
                end
                if (z <= Z1 && zold > Z1)
                    # Particle enters the CV on the right.
                    # (Contribution: – (q*weight)/dt and – momentum/dt)
                    contrib = (q * weight) / dt
                    if q > 0
                        @CUDA.atomic IonCurrentArray[1] -= contrib
                    else
                        @CUDA.atomic ElectronCurrentArray[1] -= contrib
                    end
                    @CUDA.atomic MomentumFluxArray[1] -= momentum / dt
                end

                # --- Left boundary at z = Z0 ---
                if (z <= Z0 && zold > Z0)
                    # Particle leaves the CV on the left.
                    # (Note: although the left boundary is at a lower z,
                    #  we count a particle leaving as a positive contribution to net flux.)
                    contrib = (q * weight) / dt
                    if q > 0
                        @CUDA.atomic IonCurrentArray[1] += contrib
                    else
                        @CUDA.atomic ElectronCurrentArray[1] += contrib
                    end
                    @CUDA.atomic MomentumFluxArray[1] += momentum / dt
                end
                if (z > Z0 && zold <= Z0)
                    # Particle enters the CV on the left.
                    contrib = (q * weight) / dt
                    if q > 0
                        @CUDA.atomic IonCurrentArray[1] -= contrib
                    else
                        @CUDA.atomic ElectronCurrentArray[1] -= contrib
                    end
                    @CUDA.atomic MomentumFluxArray[1] -= momentum / dt
                end

                # --- For particles that remain inside the CV ---
                if (z >= Z0 && z <= Z1)
                    @CUDA.atomic EnergyArray[1] += energy
                    @CUDA.atomic ChargeArray[1] += q * weight
                end
            end
        end
        return
    end  # end kernel

    # Launch the kernel over all particles.
    N = length(myParticle.alive)
    threads = 256
    blocks = cld(N, threads)
    @cuda threads=threads blocks=blocks CV_fluxanalysis_kernel(
         myParticle.PosArray, myParticle.PosArray_old,
         myParticle.VelArray, myParticle.VelArray_old,
         myParticle.alive,
         myParticle.qArray,
         myParticle.mArray,
         myParticle.superParticleSizeArray,
         myParticle.rCellNum, myParticle.zCellNum,
         myDomain.phi,
         dt,
         EnergyArray, ChargeArray,
         IonCurrentArray, ElectronCurrentArray,
         MomentumFluxArray)

    # Copy the results back from the GPU.
    energy         = Array(EnergyArray)[1]
    charge         = Array(ChargeArray)[1]
    ion_current    = Array(IonCurrentArray)[1]
    electron_current = Array(ElectronCurrentArray)[1]
    momentum_flux  = Array(MomentumFluxArray)[1]

    return energy, charge, ion_current, electron_current, momentum_flux
end

Explanation

  1. Kernel Parameters and Setup:

    • In addition to the particle arrays (PosArray, PosArray_old, etc.), we pass along the particle properties needed to compute momentum, energy, and the weight (from superParticleSizeArray).
    • We also pass the electric potential phi (from your domain) along with the cell indices rCellNum and zCellNum so that the potential energy can be gathered (using a helper function gather).

  2. Determining a Crossing:

    • The kernel checks, for each particle (only if it is “alive”), whether the particle has crossed one of the CV boundaries by comparing its current zzz position with its previous position.
    • For each crossing event the code “deposits” a contribution. In our example we always take the contribution to be contrib=q×weightdt ,\texttt{contrib} = \frac{q \times \texttt{weight}}{dt}\,,contrib=dtq×weight​, and similarly we deposit momentumdt\frac{\texttt{momentum}}{dt}dtmomentum​ for the momentum flux.
    • The sign is chosen so that a crossing from inside to outside (leaving) adds a positive contribution while one from outside to inside (entering) subtracts that amount.

  3. Separating Electrons and Ions:

    • We use the sign of qqq (from qArray) to decide whether the contribution belongs to the ion or electron “bucket.” (Electrons typically have q<0q<0q<0 and ions q>0q>0q>0.)

  4. Energy and Charge Deposition:

    • For particles that remain inside the CV (i.e. Z0≤z≤Z1Z_0 \le z \le Z_1Z0​≤z≤Z1​) the kernel deposits their energy and charge into EnergyArray and ChargeArray.

  5. Atomic Operations:

    • Because many threads might add to the same variable, we use @CUDA.atomic to update the output arrays safely.

  6. Using the Function:

    • After the kernel completes, the function copies the one-element arrays back to the host and returns the five quantities: total energy inside the CV, total charge inside the CV, net ion current (in units of charge per time step), net electron current, and net momentum flux (in units of momentum per time step).

You can call the function (for example) as

julia
energy, charge, ion_current, electron_current, momentum_flux = CV_fluxanalysis(myParticle, myDomain, Z0, Z1, dt)

and then (if desired) divide the current and momentum flux by the CV’s cross‐sectional area to obtain densities.

Note:
This is just one possible implementation. In practice you may wish to adjust the sign conventions, split the flux contributions per boundary, or deposit onto a grid (using a shape function) if you need a spatial profile rather than a single net number.

You said:
If I add all z-momentum of particles inside the CV, is it true that the thrust would be the derivative of that? Similarly, if I differentiate the total charge in CV, will it give current?

Yes, in principle that’s correct—but with some important caveats. The ideas come directly from conservation laws:

  1. Momentum and Thrust:
    If you sum up the z‐component of the momentum (i.e. mivz,im_i v_{z,i}mi​vz,i​) for all particles inside your control volume (CV), then its time derivative (i.e. the rate of change of the total momentum) represents the net force acting on that CV. In many contexts (for example, in rocket propulsion) this net force is identified as the thrust. This follows from Newton’s second law (or the Reynolds transport theorem in a continuum setting):

    Fz=ddt(∑imivz,i).F_z = \frac{d}{dt}\left(\sum_i m_i v_{z,i}\right).Fz​=dtd​(i∑​mi​vz,i​).

    However, note that in a PIC simulation you must ensure that you have a well-defined closed control volume and that you account for any forces or momentum sources/sinks (such as fields or collisions) that might be present.

  2. Charge and Current:
    Similarly, if you differentiate the total charge contained within the CV with respect to time, you obtain the net current leaving (or entering) the CV. This is a statement of charge conservation:

    ddt(∫CVρ dV)=−∫CSJ⋅n dA,\frac{d}{dt} \left(\int_{\text{CV}} \rho \, dV\right) = -\int_{\text{CS}} \mathbf{J}\cdot\mathbf{n}\, dA,dtd​(∫CV​ρdV)=−∫CS​J⋅ndA,

    so if you compute the time derivative of the total charge (the left-hand side), you are effectively measuring the net current (flux) across the boundaries (the right-hand side). In your particle-based simulation, the change in the total charge within the CV per unit time would correspond to the net charge flux (current).

Important Caveats:

  • Discrete vs. Continuous: In a numerical PIC simulation, you are working with discrete time steps and particles. The derivative must be approximated (for example, as a finite difference over one or more time steps), and one has to be cautious about how well this approximates the “true” continuous derivative.

  • Boundary Definitions: The control volume must be clearly defined. Particles may cross the boundaries during a time step, so proper accounting (as in the flux deposition you discussed) is needed.

  • Sources/Sinks: If there are any sources or sinks (e.g., due to ionization, recombination, or external fields) within the CV, then the simple time derivative of the total momentum or charge won’t equal just the net flux through the boundaries. You’d have to account for those additional terms.

In summary, provided you are considering a closed system (or a well‐defined CV with proper boundary treatment) and use an appropriate numerical approximation for the time derivative, then:

  • The time derivative of the total z‐momentum inside the CV gives you the net force (thrust) in the z‐direction.
  • The time derivative of the total charge inside the CV gives you the net current flowing out of (or into) the CV.

This is exactly what the conservation laws imply.

There is indeed sources and sinks within the CV, then what method should I use?

Balancing sources and flux

When sources and sinks are present within the control volume, the net flux of momentum or charge must balance the derivative of the quantity within the control volume, including the source/sink terms.

Applying the theorem

Using the Reynolds Transport Theorem, you embed a source term in equations for charge and momentum balance in the control volume, aligning flux and time derivative with internal sources/sinks.

Separating contributions

To manage internal sources and sinks in flux analysis, calculate them independently within a simulation, then integrate these findings into the overall flux to ensure an accurate balance.

Laying out the options

I’m considering applying the divergence theorem for boundary flux and adding source terms to align internal changes, or using a control volume method to sum particle contributions at boundaries.

Validating conservation

Using a control volume method, calculate boundary flux by summing particle contributions, then match it with internal sources or sinks to confirm the net conservation law.

Ensuring precise flux

To accurately account for sources and sinks, compute boundary fluxes by summing particle contributions and combine them with internal source measurements to verify the net conservation law.

Determining net flux

To compute the net flux, tally boundary flux and subtract internal source/sink contributions using the Reynolds Transport Theorem, ensuring alignment with the conservation law equations.

When sources or sinks (for momentum or charge) are present inside your control volume, you can’t rely solely on the time derivative of the total quantity in the CV to represent the net flux through its boundaries. Instead, you must account for these internal production or loss terms. Here are a couple of approaches you might use:

1. Direct Flux Deposition at the Boundaries

Method:

  • Detect Boundary Crossings: Rather than computing the derivative of the internal quantity, directly record every particle that crosses a boundary.
  • Deposit Flux Contributions: Each time a particle crosses a boundary (using its old and new positions), deposit its contribution (e.g., q×weight/Δtq \times \text{weight}/\Delta tq×weight/Δt for charge or m vz×weight/Δtm\,v_z \times \text{weight}/\Delta tmvz​×weight/Δt for momentum) into a flux accumulator.
  • Advantages:
    • This method gives you the actual net flux through the boundaries regardless of what happens inside the CV.
    • It bypasses the complication that internal sources/sinks would add to (or subtract from) the time derivative of the total quantity.

Implementation:
This is essentially what you were doing with your kernel function for flux analysis. By checking the conditions z>Z1z > Z_1z>Z1​ and zold≤Z1z_{\text{old}} \le Z_1zold​≤Z1​ (or similar for the left boundary), you capture the particles leaving or entering, and you sum their contributions. This method directly measures the net flux through the CV boundaries.

2. Use the Reynolds Transport Theorem

Method:
The Reynolds Transport Theorem (or conservation law) states that for a quantity Ψ\PsiΨ (like momentum or charge) the following holds:

ddt∫CVΨ dV=−∫CSΨ v⋅n dA+∫CVS dV,\frac{d}{dt} \int_{CV} \Psi\,dV = -\int_{CS} \Psi\, \mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}\, dA + \int_{CV} S\, dV,dtd​∫CV​ΨdV=−∫CS​Ψv⋅ndA+∫CV​SdV,

where:

  • ∫CVΨ dV\int_{CV} \Psi\,dV∫CV​ΨdV is the total quantity in the control volume,
  • −∫CSΨ v⋅n dA-\int_{CS} \Psi\, \mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\, dA−∫CS​Ψv⋅ndA is the net flux out of the control surface,
  • ∫CVS dV\int_{CV} S\, dV∫CV​SdV represents internal source (or sink) terms.

How to Use This:

  • Measure the Rate of Change: Compute the time derivative of the total quantity (e.g., total momentum or total charge) inside the CV.
  • Estimate Internal Sources/Sinks: Independently measure or model the internal source terms SSS (for example, from ionization, recombination, collisions, or other processes that add or remove momentum or charge).
  • Subtract Sources/Sinks: Rearrange the equation to solve for the net boundary flux: Flux through CS=−ddt(∫CVΨ dV)+∫CVS dV.\text{Flux through CS} = -\frac{d}{dt}\left(\int_{CV} \Psi\,dV\right) + \int_{CV} S\, dV.Flux through CS=−dtd​(∫CV​ΨdV)+∫CV​SdV.
  • Advantages:
    • This formulation gives you a way to account for known source/sink terms.
    • It can be useful if you have accurate measurements or models for the internal source/sink processes.

Challenges:

  • Accurately computing the time derivative (using finite differences) can be noisy, especially in particle simulations.
  • Obtaining a reliable measure of the source/sink term SSS within the CV might be nontrivial, depending on your simulation’s complexity.

Which Method Should You Use?

  • If you can directly record particle crossings:
    Use direct flux deposition at the boundaries. This approach avoids the need to differentiate the internal quantity and then correct for sources and sinks.

  • If you need to use the integral properties of the CV:
    Apply the Reynolds Transport Theorem. In that case, you must independently compute the contributions from the sources and sinks within the CV and then combine them with the time derivative of the internal quantity to obtain the net flux.

In many PIC simulations, the direct deposition method is more robust because it “captures” the flux in one step, rather than relying on the sometimes noisy time derivative of the internal sum and then adjusting for sources/sinks.

Summary

  • Direct Flux Deposition:
    – Identify particles crossing the boundaries and sum their contributions.
    – This method gives you the net flux directly and avoids complications from internal sources/sinks.

  • Reynolds Transport Theorem Approach:
    – Compute the time derivative of the total quantity in the CV and subtract (or add) the internal source/sink contributions.
    – This requires careful estimation of the source/sink terms and a good finite-difference estimate of the time derivative.

Choose the method that best suits your simulation framework and the accuracy with which you can measure the internal source/sink terms.

Here the kernel function BC_absorbZ_reflectR_kernel is defined inside BC_absorbZ_reflectR. How to Fix It

Move the kernel function to global scope. For example, define the kernel outside of any other function:

julia
using CUDA

# Define the kernel at global scope.
function BC_absorbZ_reflectR_kernel(
    PosArray, PosArray_old,
    VelArray, VelArray_old,
    alive, r_MAX, z_MAX, qArray, mArray, superParticleSizeArray
)
    idx = threadIdx().x + (blockIdx().x - 1) * blockDim().x
    if idx <= length(alive)
        if alive[idx] == 1
            r = sqrt(PosArray[1,idx]^2 + PosArray[2,idx]^2)
            z = PosArray[3,idx]
            zold = PosArray_old[3,idx]
            q = qArray[idx]

            if z > z_MAX[1]
                # Remove particles above the z-boundary.
                @inbounds alive[idx] = 0
            elseif z < 0.0
                # Remove particles below z = 0.
                @inbounds alive[idx] = 0
            # Radial boundary
            elseif r > r_MAX[1]
                # Reflect particles at the radial boundary.
                @inbounds PosArray[1,idx] = PosArray_old[1,idx]
                @inbounds PosArray[2,idx] = PosArray_old[2,idx]
                @inbounds VelArray_old[1,idx] = VelArray[1,idx]
                @inbounds VelArray_old[2,idx] = VelArray[2,idx]
                @inbounds VelArray[1,idx] *= -1
                @inbounds VelArray[2,idx] *= -1
            end
        end
    end
    return
end

# Then, define your boundary condition function that calls the kernel.
function BC_absorbZ_reflectR(myParticle, myDomain)
    threads = 256
    blocks = cld(length(myParticle.alive), threads)
    @cuda threads=threads blocks=blocks BC_absorbZ_reflectR_kernel(
        myParticle.PosArray,
        myParticle.PosArray_old,
        myParticle.VelArray,
        myParticle.VelArray_old,
        myParticle.alive,
        myDomain.r_MAX,
        myDomain.z_MAX,
        myParticle.qArray,
        myParticle.mArray,
        myParticle.superParticleSizeArray
    )
    return nothing
end

Explanation

  • Global Kernel Definition:
    By moving BC_absorbZ_reflectR_kernel to the global scope, you ensure that it does not capture any outer variables. All necessary data (arrays and parameters) are passed in explicitly as arguments.

  • Explicit Passing of Data:
    In the kernel call via @cuda, you pass all the arrays (from myParticle and myDomain) explicitly. This way the GPU code does not need to “reach out” to any undefined outer variable like myParticle.

  • Kernel Launch Parameters:
    The launch configuration is computed on the host (with cld(length(myParticle.alive), threads)), which is fine.

A great choice is the TikZ package (which is part of the PGF/TikZ suite). TikZ is extremely versatile and widely used for creating high-quality vector graphics directly within LaTeX. With TikZ, you can:

  • Draw detailed schematics, diagrams, and scientific illustrations.
  • Use a variety of built-in shapes, lines, and curves to represent components.
  • Customize styles, colors, and node placements to fit your schematic needs.
  • Incorporate additional libraries (such as calc, positioning, or even 3dplot for 3D schematics) to enhance your drawings.

For a schematic of an ion thruster, you might combine basic shapes to represent the thruster body, grids, ion sources, and exhaust plumes.
